%% Diagram: Active expiration sweep
%% Type: sequence
%%{init: {'htmlLabels': false}}%%
sequenceDiagram
    participant CRON as Hourly cron
    participant SWEEP as Expiration sweeper
    participant DB as PostgreSQL
    participant S3 as Object storage
    participant R as Redis

    CRON->>SWEEP: trigger
    loop until empty (LIMIT 10k per batch)
        SWEEP->>DB: SELECT id FROM pastes<br/>WHERE expires_at < NOW()<br/>AND deleted_at IS NULL<br/>LIMIT 10000
        DB-->>SWEEP: batch of expired ids
        SWEEP->>S3: DELETE pastes/{id}.zst<br/>DELETE highlighted/{id}.html
        S3-->>SWEEP: 204 No Content
        SWEEP->>R: DEL paste:{id}
        SWEEP->>DB: UPDATE pastes SET deleted_at = NOW()<br/>WHERE id = ANY($batch)
        DB-->>SWEEP: rows updated
    end
    Note over SWEEP,DB: Lazy read check still enforces<br/>expiry between sweeps, so a paste<br/>that expires mid-cycle still returns 410.
